I leave my room and head downstairs to the kitchen. There is a piece of paper on the table on top of which are two sets of red pills. On the paper above the first set is "10:00" and above the second set "2:00". The time on the stove says 10:58... woops. This time, I take both pills without a problem, but I still feel groggy and awful, like I'm moving with weights tied to me. It sucks that medicine doesn't work faster.

How long does it take them to kick in? I look at the clock. 10:59 becomes [[11:00]].

:: 11:00

<<audio "rotary-ring-distant" loop play>>\
\
Somewhere, a phone starts ringing. It must be the neighbor's phone because it sounds old. Our landline doesn't sound like that, and my cell definitely doesn't sound like that. 

No, wait. Dad //does// have an old phone in his office, but no one ever calls it. I wonder who would be calling that phone? Dad doesn't like me going in his office when he's not there, but I should probably [[tell whoever it is to call his cell]].

:: tell whoever it is to call his cell

Dad's office is across the house, next to the front door. Sometimes he keeps the door locked, but most of the time he forgets. Today it opens easily, and I <<linkappend "go inside.">><<audio "rotary-ring-distant" stop>><<audio "rotary-ring" loop play>>

Jeez, these old phones are really loud. It's kinda freaky. There's no caller ID or anything like on my cell, just this big circle thing that you dial with. How did people ever used to know who was calling? It could be anyone on the other end...

I look out the front window, but no one's there. I'm dumb. I kinda expected someone to be watching me from the sidewalk with a phone to their ear.

Oh, right. I should [[answer the phone]].
